04212nam a22006495i 9780292733909DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211987txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927339097 a10.7560/7245632doi  a(DE-B1597)588294  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGN671.T5bG35 1987 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.8/3/0996122191 aGailey, Christine Ward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKinship to Kingship :bGender Hierarchy and State Formation in the Tongan Islands /cChristine Ward Gailey. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1987  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: The Quest for Origins -- ti. The Subordination of Women: Gender in Transitions from Kinship to Class -- t2. State Formation -- tPart Two: Gender and Kinship Relations in Precontact Tonga -- t3. Authority and Ambiguity: Rethinking Tongan Kinship -- t4. The Reproduction of Ambiguity: Succession Disputes, Marriage Patterns, and Foreigners -- t5. Division of Labor -- t6. Exchange and Value -- t7. Gender Relations at Contact -- tPart Three: Conversion, Commodities, and State Formation -- t8. Early Contact -- t9. Missionaries: The Crusade for Christian Civilization -- t10. A Native Kingdom: Creating Class and Gender Stratification -- t11. Changing Production: Commodities, Tribute, and Forced Labor -- t12. Dialectics of Class and State Formation -- tAppendix: Sources and Methods -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHave women always been subordinated? If not, why and how did women’s subordination develop? Kinship to Kingship was the first book to examine in detail how and why gender relations become skewed when classes and the state emerge in a society. Using a Marxist-feminist approach, Christine Ward Gailey analyzes women’s status in one society over three hundred years, from a period when kinship relations organized property, work, distribution, consumption, and reproduction to a class-based state society. Although this study focuses on one group of islands, Tonga, in the South Pacific, the author discusses processes that can be seen through the neocolonial world. This ethnohistorical study argues that evolution from a kin-based society to one organized along class lines necessarily entails the subordination of women. And the opposite is also held to be true: state and class formation cannot be understood without analyzing gender and the status of women. Of interest to students of anthropology, political science, sociology, and women’s studies, this work is a major contribution to social history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAcculturationzTonga. 0aKinship - Tonga. 0aKinshipzTonga. 0aSex rolezTonga. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72456340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292733909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292733909/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK